Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[_Yersinia pseudotuberculosis_ infections are known to have led to significant lethality in European brown hare (_Lepus europaeus_) populations especially during the cold and wet seasons. During a serosurvey in hare populations in North-Rhine Westphalia, Germany, published in 2004, a total of 89.6 percent of the 230 animals tested were seropositive. It was postulated that subclinical yersiniosis could have been related to the decline of European brown hare populations in Germany.

It will be interesting to note if the current outbreak means a recent introduction of the bacterium into the hare population of Cyprus or just the reflection of the 1st detection of an established situation.

For background information on _Y. pseudotuberculosis_, readers are referred to the comprehensive commentary of Mod.ML in ProMED-mail posting 20110502.1362. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1G17.]
